                {
                  "nickName": "Guest User",
                  "regionCode": "",
                  "content": "Upon checking out, we mentioned how our room was tired and lacked cleanliness. I wasn\u2019t prepared for the lady at reception to smile and acknowledge that \u201cthey know\u201d. There wasn\u2019t an apology.   It seems poor practice to sell rooms when they knowingly have issues.   - Marks on pillowcases.  - Hole in the duvet cover, leaving a corner of the duvet to poke out.  - Dirty water glasses.  - Smears across bedroom mirror.   - Carpet is marked in many places (you wouldn\u2019t want to walk barefoot).  - The toilet seat is only anchored to one side (so it moves constantly).  - Enclosed shower leaks into the bathroom.  - Shaver plug charged toothbrush intermittently.  - Not sure if the extractor worked; as the bathroom mirrors took a long time to clear after showering.  - The second keycard didn\u2019t work.  - Aircon felt non-existent but was still noisy.  - No net or privacy filters on windows, so you either had to draw the blackout curtains completely or be seen by the adjacent hotel\u2019s occupants.   Room flaws:   - The rainfall shower was terrific, but the small cubical made it impossible to move away from the water to apply soap/shampoo.  - The bedside light switches were too far away to reach from the bed.  - Windows looked double sealed, but you could still hear a local bar and their customers at 4 am from the third floor.  -   Breakfast:  - A little chaotic! Staff tried their best, but they seemed to struggle with replacing food.  - Cooked breakfast buffet was boiled to an inch of its life, no flavour in anything.  The pros:   - very good size bathroom, with separate shower and bath. Modern looking.  - a good central location.  - local parking discount (25%)  302 Saturday 25th Sep",
